# TypeScript Strict Typing

Apply these rules to all TypeScript code in this project.

## Function Return Types

Every function, method, and arrow function must declare an explicit return type.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
function getUser(id: string) {
  return db.findUser(id);
}

const parse = (raw: string) => JSON.parse(raw);

// ✅ GOOD
function getUser(id: string): User | null {
  return db.findUser(id);
}

const parse = (raw: string): ParsedPayload => JSON.parse(raw) as ParsedPayload;
```

## Variable Types

Every declared variable must have an explicit type annotation. Do not rely on inference for `const`, `let`, or destructuring bindings.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
const users = await fetchUsers();
let count = 0;
const { name, age } = user;

// ✅ GOOD
const users: User[] = await fetchUsers();
let count: number = 0;
const { name, age }: { name: string; age: number } = user;
```

## Forbidden Types

You are **forbidden** from using `any` or `unknown` as a type annotation, generic argument, cast target, or assertion result.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
function handle(data: any): unknown { ... }
const value = response as any;

// ✅ GOOD — use a concrete type or a well-defined union/interface
function handle(data: ApiPayload): ApiResult { ... }
const value: ApiPayload = response as ApiPayload;
```

If `any` or `unknown` seems necessary, **stop and ask the user for permission** before using it. Explain why a concrete type cannot be used.

## When Types Are Unclear

Prefer narrowing, type guards, generics with constraints, or defining a small interface over falling back to loose types.
